e, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Maxstoke Castle, Maxstoke, Warwickshire, England":"Maxstoke Castle, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1361–1409":"1361–1409","1350–1375":"1350–1375","1352–1417":"1352–1417","1354–1383":"1354–1383","1360–1411":"1360–1411","1364–1400":"1364–1400","1365–1398":"1365–1398","1350–1422":"1350–1422","1387–1412":"1387–1412","1328–1398":"1328–1398","1328–1384":"1328–1384","1352":"1352","1384":"1384","1361":"1361","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1412":"1412","1422":"1422","1400":"1400","1411":"1411","1387":"1387","1398":"1398","1365":"1365","1354":"1354","6 September 1398":"6 September 1398","1364":"1364","1375":"1375","1409":"1409","before 26 June 1384":"before 26 June 1384","1417":"1417","1328":"1328","Maxstoke, Warwickshire, England":"Maxstoke, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Maxstoke Castle, Maxstoke, Warwickshire, England":"Maxstoke Castle, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clinton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Louth, Westmeath) and Scottish: shortened form of   McClinton  .","English: habitational name, either from Glympton in Oxfordshire, named as ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) on the Glym river’, a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright stream’, or from Glinton in Northamptonshire, early recorded as <i>Clinton</i> (named with an unrecorded Old English element akin to Middle Low German <i>glinde</i> ‘enclosure, fence’ + Old English <i>tūn</i>). The surname was taken to Ireland in or before the 16th century.","History: Charles Clinton (born 1690 in Longford, Ireland) organized a group of colonists and founded the settlement of Little Britain, Ulster County, NY, in 1731. His son George Clinton (1739–1812) was governor of NY (1777–95), and they had many prominent descendants. — An English aristocratic family called <i>Clinton</i> was founded by Geoffrey de Clinton (flourished 1130), who held lands at Glympton, Oxfordshire. He was chamberlain and treasurer to Henry I (1100–35)."],"variants":[{"name":"McClinton","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Fhionntain</b> (Scottish), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntáin</b> (Irish) ‘son of the servant (i.e. devotee) of (Saint) <i>Fionntan</i>’, whose name has been explained as ‘the white ancient’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Clinton was born in 1361, her father, John de Clinton 3rd Lord Clinton, was 11358 and her mother, Idonea de Saye, was 33. She had at least 1 daughter with Mr Anthony Sutton. She died in 1409, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1361–1409":"1361–1409","1350–1375":"1350–1375","1352–1417":"1352–1417","1354–1383":"1354–1383","1360–1411":"1360–1411","1364–1400":"1364–1400","1365–1398":"1365–1398","1350–1422":"1350–1422","1387–1412":"1387–1412","1328–1398":"1328–1398","1328–1384":"1328–1384","1352":"1352","1384":"1384","1361":"1361","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1412":"1412","1422":"1422","1400":"1400","1411":"1411","1387":"1387","1398":"1398","1365":"1365","1354":"1354","6 September 1398":"6. september 1398","1364":"1364","1375":"1375","1409":"1409","before 26 June 1384":"enne 26. juunit 1384","1417":"1417","1328":"1328","Maxstoke, Warwickshire, England":"Maxstoke, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Maxstoke Castle, Maxstoke, Warwickshire, England":"Maxstoke Castle, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1361–1409":"1361–1409","1350–1375":"1350–1375","1352–1417":"1352–1417","1354–1383":"1354–1383","1360–1411":"1360–1411","1364–1400":"1364–1400","1365–1398":"1365–1398","1350–1422":"1350–1422","1387–1412":"1387–1412","1328–1398":"1328–1398","1328–1384":"1328–1384","1352":"1352","1384":"1384","1361":"1361","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1412":"1412","1422":"1422","1400":"1400","1411":"1411","1387":"1387","1398":"1398","1365":"1365","1354":"1354","6 September 1398":"6